- VSCode Version: 0.10.13-insider
- OS Version: Windows 10

I am properly enjoying the new _insider_ release - it offers so much! - and it is with great regret that I must file this first bug...

Steps to Reproduce:
1. Create a block of text such as this one:

```
var gulp = require('gulp');
var path = require('path');
var rimraf = require('rimraf');
var isarray = require('isarray');
var merge = require('merge-stream');
var concat = require('gulp-concat');
var newer = require('gulp-newer');
```
1. Place the caret on the first line, on the left of the `var` keyword.
2. Hold `alt + shift` and left-click on the right hand side of the `var` keyword on the last line to make a column selection.
3. Observe that if the mouse was even a few pixels overlapped with the `space` character, the column of spaces will also be included in the selection - the selection is biased towards the right.
4. Now repeat step two and make a single-line selection by holding shift and clicking on the right hand side of the `var` keyword on the _first_ line - observe that the selection is biased to the left - i.e. you have to be almost completely past the `space` character or else it is _excluded_ from the selection.

Clearly, column-select's behaviour is non-traditional in this regard.

Personally, I prefer to "draw" my column selections like you can in full-fat Visual Studio when you hold down `alt`. This shift-select style is fine but it should at least be consistent with U.I. norms.

- VSCode Version: 0.10.13-insider
- OS Version: window 7 Pro SP1

Using VSCode and Babel/ES7 for JavaScript, I have issues when indenting code using [the object spread operator](https://github.com/sebmarkbage/ecmascript-rest-spread). This specification allow to write:

``` javascript
    let { x, y, ...z } = { x: 1, y: 2, a: 3, b: 4 };
    x; // 1
    y; // 2
    z; // { a: 3, b: 4 }
```

Steps to Reproduce:

1 . write this code:

``` javascript
function main() {
  var p; //a promise

  var callback = () => {
    var data = { x: 1, y: 2, a: 3, b: 4 };
    let { x, y, ...z } = data;
    x; // 1
    y; // 2
    z; // { a: 3, b: 4 }
  };

  p.then( callback );
}
```

All works fine when auto indenting this code

2 . When trying to make `callback` an anonymous function, it doesn't indent as wanted anymore:

``` javascript
function main() {
  var p; //a promise

  p.then(() => {
    var data = { x: 1, y: 2, a: 3, b: 4 };
    let { x, y, ...z } = data;
x; // 1
y; // 2
z; // { a: 3, b: 4 }
  } );
}
```

Has anyone meet this problem?

- VSCode Version: 0.10.11
- OS Version: Windows 10

I have a promise that takes just over a second to complete, but due to [this code](https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/blob/master/src/vs/workbench/node/extensionHostProcess.ts#L53) (shown below) it is always rejected.

```
process.on('unhandledRejection', (reason, promise) => {
    unhandledPromises.push(promise);
    setTimeout(() => {
        const idx = unhandledPromises.indexOf(promise);
        if (idx >= 0) {
            unhandledPromises.splice(idx, 1);
            console.warn('rejected promise not handled with 1 second');
            onUnexpectedError(reason);
        }
    }, 1000);
});
```

I would like to be able to specify a timeout manually for my promise to allow it to run for 2 seconds _(for example)_ before timing out and being rejected. (1 second should remain as the default timeout)

- VSCode Version: 0.10.13 (insider)
- OS Version: OS X 10.10.5

Steps to Reproduce:

1.create a new .js file and past the following example code in:

```
export default function promiseMiddleware () {
    return next => action => {
        const {promise , type , ...rest} = action;
        if (!promise) return next(action);
        const SUCCESS = type;
        const REQUEST = type + '_REQUEST';
        const FAILURE = type + '_FAILURE';

        next({...rest,type: REQUEST});

        return promise
            .then(res => {
                next({res,type: SUCCESS});
                return true;
            })
            .catch(error => {
                next({...rest,error,type: FAILURE});
                return false;
            });
    };
}
```

2.`cmd-shift-p` then type `format code`

With the spread operator (`...rest`) this causes a weird formatting issue (indent level) resulting in:

```
